# Investigation 003 — Wireshark Exploit Kit Analysis

Date: 19/05/2026
Analyst: Sadiq Ssali Abdulaziz
Tool Used: Wireshark
Data Source: PCAP file - 2014-traffic-analysis-exercise
Source: Malware-traffic-analysis.net

Overview
I analysed a packet containing 3053 packets to identify 
malicious network activities

Protocol Breakdown
Protocol          Percentage
Frame             100
Ethernet          100
IPv4              98.7
IPv6              0.7
TCP               96.7
TLS               12.2
HTTP              2.6

Suspicious Domains
Domain                                Count    Verdict
www.ciniholland.nl                    20       Compromised
24corp-shop.com                       3        Malicious
stand.trustandprobaterealty.com       12       Malicious

Attack Chain
Step 1: Victim searched Bing for ciniholland.nl
Step 2: Victim clicked and visited www.ciniholland.nl
        which was a normal looking but compromised site
Step 3: ciniholland.nl redirected victim to 24corp-shop.com
Step 4: 24corp-shop.com redirected victim to
        stand.trustandprobaterealty.com
Step 5: Exploit kit delivered SWF, JAR, XML and MP3 
        exploits to victims browser
Step 6: Victims outdated IE8 on Windows 7 got infected

Victim Details
IP Address: 172.16.165.165
Operating System: Windows 7
Browser: Internet Explorer 8 which is weak and outdated

Wireshark Filters Used
http
http contains "trustandprobaterealty"
http contains "24corp-shop"
http contains "ciniholland"
http.request.method == "GET"

Verdict
Malicious activity confirmed. Victim visited a normal 
looking website which was compromised and silently 
redirected them through two malicious sites until an 
exploit kit attacked their outdated IE8 browser 
on Windows 7.

What I Learned
- How to identify exploit kit traffic
- SWF and JAR files are used in browser exploits
- PHPSSESID in URLs is a sign of exploit kit tracking
- Attackers use redirect chains to hide where the 
  attack is really coming from
- Compromised legitimate websites are used as entry 
  points to avoid suspicion
